{"slug": "rgb7904-cow-beauty-pageant", "title_mn": "Үхрийн гоо сайхны тэмцээн", "title_en": "Cow Beauty Pageant", "statement_mn": "Фармер Жон хоёр толботой үнээнүүд моодонд орсон гэж сонсоод, хоёр толботой үнээнүүдийн сүрэг худалдаж авсан. Харамсалтай нь моод хурдан өөрчлөгдөж, одоо ганц толботой үнээ моод болжээ! ФЖ хоёр толбыг нэгтгэж, үнээнүүдээ будахыг хүсч байна.

Үнээний арьс нь N x M (1 ≤ N, M ≤ 50) хэмжээтэй тэмдэгтүүдийн сүлжээгээр дүрслэгдэнэ. Жишээ нь:

```
................
..XXXX....XXX...
...XXXX....XX...
.XXXX......XXX..
........XXXXX...
.........XXX....
```

Энд 'X' тэмдэгт нь толбын хэсгийг илэрхийлнэ. Хоёр 'X' нь босоо эсвэл хөндлөн зэргэлдээ байвал (диагональ нь тооцогдохгүй) нэг толбонд хамаарна. Дээрх зураг дээр яг хоёр толбо байна. ФЖ-ийн бүх үнээнүүд яг хоёр толботой.

ФЖ хоёр толбыг нэг болгон нэгтгэхийн тулд аль болох бага будаг хэрэглэхийг хүсч байна. Дээрх жишээнд тэр ердөө гурван нэмэлт 'X' тэмдэгт будаж болно (шинэ тэмдэгтүүдийг доор '*' -аар тэмдэглэв):

```
................
..XXXX....XXX...
...XXXX*...XX...
.XXXX..**..XXX..
........XXXXX...
.........XXX....
```

ФЖ-д хоёр толбыг нэг том толбо болгон нэгтгэхэд хэдэн шинэ 'X' тэмдэгт будах шаардлагатайг тодорхойлоход туслана уу.", "statement_en": "Hearing that the latest fashion trend was cows with two spots on their hides, Farmer John has purchased an entire herd of two-spot cows. Unfortunately, fashion trends tend to change quickly, and the most popular current fashion is cows with only one spot! FJ wants to make his herd more fashionable by painting each of his cows in such a way that merges their two spots into one.

The hide of a cow is represented by an N by M (1 ≤ N, M ≤ 50) grid of characters like this:

```
................
..XXXX....XXX...
...XXXX....XX...
.XXXX......XXX..
........XXXXX...
.........XXX....
```

Here, each 'X' denotes part of a spot. Two 'X's belong to the same spot if they are vertically or horizontally adjacent (diagonally adjacent does not count), so the figure above has exactly two spots. All of the cows in FJ's herd have exactly two spots.

FJ wants to use as little paint as possible to merge the two spots into one. In the example above, he can do this by painting only three additional characters with 'X's (the new characters are marked with '*'s below to make them easier to see):

```
................
..XXXX....XXX...
...XXXX*...XX...
.XXXX..**..XXX..
........XXXXX...
.........XXX....
```

Please help FJ determine the minimum number of new 'X's he must paint in order to merge two spots into one large spot.", "input_format_mn": "Эхний мөрөнд хоёр бүхэл тоо N ба M (1 ≤ N, M ≤ 50) өгөгдөнө. Дараагийн N мөрөнд тус бүр M тэмдэгтээс бүрдэх сүлжээ өгөгдөнө. Тэмдэгт нь '.' (цэг) эсвэл 'X' байна. Сүлжээнд яг хоёр толбо (холбогдсон 'X' бүрэлдэхүүн) байна.", "input_format_en": "The first line contains two integers N and M (1 ≤ N, M ≤ 50). The next N lines each contain M characters describing the grid. Each character is either '.' (dot) or 'X'. There are exactly two spots (connected components of 'X') in the grid.", "output_format_mn": "Хоёр толбыг нэгтгэхэд шаардлагатай хамгийн бага тооны шинэ 'X' тэмдэгтийг илэрхийлэх нэг бүхэл тоог хэвлэнэ.", "output_format_en": "Print a single integer — the minimum number of new 'X' characters needed to merge the two spots into one.", "constraints_mn": "- 1 ≤ N, M ≤ 50
- Сүлжээнд яг хоёр толбо ('X' тэмдэгтүүд) байна.
- Толбо нь босоо болон хөндлөн зэргэлдээ байдлаар холбогдоно (диагональ биш).", "constraints_en": "- 1 ≤ N, M ≤ 50
- There are exactly two spots (connected components of 'X') in the grid.
- Spots are connected vertically or horizontally (not diagonally).", "difficulty": "medium", "tags": ["bfs", "shortest-path", "grid"], "time_limit_ms": 1000, "memory_limit_kb": 65536, "xp_reward": 20, "reference_cpp": "#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

const int dx[4] = {0, 0, 1, -1};
const int dy[4] = {1, -1, 0, 0};

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int N, M;
    cin >> N >> M;
    vector<string> g(N);
    for (int i = 0; i < N; i++) cin >> g[i];

    // Find the two spots (connected components of 'X')
    vector<vector<int>> comp(N, vector<int>(M, -1));
    int comp_cnt = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < N; i++) {
        for (int j = 0; j < M; j++) {
            if (g[i][j] == 'X' && comp[i][j] == -1) {
                queue<pair<int,int>> q;
                q.push({i, j});
                comp[i][j] = comp_cnt;
                while (!q.empty()) {
                    auto [x, y] = q.front(); q.pop();
                    for (int d = 0; d < 4; d++) {
                        int nx = x + dx[d], ny = y + dy[d];
                        if (nx >= 0 && nx < N && ny >= 0 && ny < M 
                            && g[nx][ny] == 'X' && comp[nx][ny] == -1) {
                            comp[nx][ny] = comp_cnt;
                            q.push({nx, ny});
                        }
                    }
                }
                comp_cnt++;
            }
        }
    }

    // BFS from spot 0: compute distance to each cell
    const int INF = 1e9;
    vector<vector<int>> dist(N, vector<int>(M, INF));
    queue<pair<int,int>> q;
    for (int i = 0; i < N; i++) {
        for (int j = 0; j < M; j++) {
            if (comp[i][j] == 0) {
                dist[i][j] = 0;
                q.push({i, j});
            }
        }
    }
    while (!q.empty()) {
        auto [x, y] = q.front(); q.pop();
        for (int d = 0; d < 4; d++) {
            int nx = x + dx[d], ny = y + dy[d];
            if (nx >= 0 && nx < N && ny >= 0 && ny < M && dist[nx][ny] == INF) {
                dist[nx][ny] = dist[x][y] + 1;
                q.push({nx, ny});
            }
        }
    }

    // Find minimum distance to spot 1
    int ans = INF;
    for (int i = 0; i < N; i++) {
        for (int j = 0; j < M; j++) {
            if (comp[i][j] == 1) {
                ans = min(ans, dist[i][j]);
            }
        }
    }

    // The answer is the minimum number of cells to fill.
    // dist[i][j] counts steps from spot 0.
    // To connect spot 0 and spot 1 via a path of new X's, 
    // if we paint cells along the path, the number of new cells painted
    // is the number of '.' cells on the path.
    // The shortest path from a cell in spot 0 to a cell in spot 1 
    // (going through '.' cells and possibly crossing other 'X' cells)
    // The number of new cells needed = dist - 1 (since the starting cell is already X, 
    // and the target cell is already X).
    // Actually, let's think:
    // dist[i][j] for a cell (i,j) in spot1 is the minimum steps from any cell in spot0 to that cell,
    // moving in 4 directions, stepping on any cell (including '.' and 'X').
    // The path: start at a spot0 cell (distance 0), then step through cells.
    // We need to paint all '.' cells along this path (except the start and end which are already X).
    // So number of new X's = dist - 1 (since both endpoints are already X).
    ans = ans - 1;

    cout << ans << "\n";

    return 0;
}
